IBM SPSS Statistics has served as the dominant desktop statistical analysis platform for over five
decades, with deep roots in academic research, social sciences, healthcare analytics, and enterprise
business intelligence. Its graphical user interface, syntax language, and extensive library of statistical
procedures have made it a familiar tool for millions of researchers, analysts, and students worldwide.
However, the software landscape has evolved dramatically in recent years, and SPSS now faces
significant challenges that undermine its relevance, accessibility, and competitive positioning in a
rapidly changing market.
This comprehensive technical report identifies and categorizes every major weakness of IBM SPSS
Statistics, spanning nine distinct problem domains: user experience and interface design, data handling
and preprocessing capabilities, statistical modeling and advanced analytics, visualization and reporting,
licensing and pricing, integration and interoperability, automation and reproducibility, performance and
scalability, and collaboration and deployment. Each weakness is analyzed with respect to its technical
root cause, its impact on end-user productivity, and its severity within the broader competitive
landscape.
For every identified weakness, this document proposes a concrete, technically grounded solution
designed for The One-Way, our next-generation statistical analysis platform. These solutions leverage
modern architectural patterns including progressive web application design, in-browser WebAssembly
computation, artificial intelligence integration, cloud-native storage, real-time collaboration frameworks,
and a modular plugin ecosystem. The proposed solutions are not merely theoretical; they are aligned
with proven technologies and architectural approaches that have been successfully deployed in
production systems across the data science industry.
The overarching vision of The One-Way is to deliver a platform that is simultaneously more powerful,
more accessible, more affordable, and more future-proof than SPSS, while preserving the familiar
workflow paradigms that existing SPSS users expect. This report serves as both a technical blueprint and
a strategic guide for achieving that vision.
